<br>
This amendment, was purported to give those who might go off to war and die, a voice in government.  And if you believe the old Students for A Democratic Society (SDS) led by infamous icons like Jane Fonda, Tom Hayden, Abby Hoffman...well then that purported reason probably sits just fine with you.<br>
<br>
In actuality, the 26th Amendment did one thing only.  It gave immense and near immediate political power to ACADEMIA, the folks who's prime area of responsibility was supposed to be non-political and strictly-the education of our kids in colleges and universities throughout the country.<br>
<br>
As a result our colleges and universities across the country have turned America from a prideful and unique melting pot of individuals into groups of multi-cultural class warfare victims on a lightning fast race for socialism.  <br>
<br>
Yep!  Through curriculum, campus voice, instigators, agitators, community studies, and a student block-voting mindset that topples communities, counties, and even state and national political offices, we are well on our way.  <br>
<br>
I have devised a way to stop it; but before I put forth this idea I want some comment from the board to see if the problem is as wide-spread as I suspect it is.  I would appreciate the name of your state when you post.<br>
<br>
I'll leave you with these two thoughts:<br>
<br>
1.  Do you know by how many votes the Republican majority in the U.S. Senate was voted out by in the 2000 general election?<br>
<br>
ANSWER:  2200 votes, which is what Senator Gorton of Washington State lost his seat by.<br>
<br>
2.  Think of 3 famous, well known colleges in the state of California.  <br>
<br>
ANSWER:  got 'em?  Now look for a website that shows which counties in the state supported Gray Davis in the recall of Nov. 2003.  Were those three colleges in a Davis county?  I'll bet all of them were.<br>
<br>
<br>
